Vladimir Putin and the risk of a Third World War
SAN FRANCISCO – Russia's invasion of Ukraine on February 24 marked the beginning of a Third World War that has the potential to destroy our civilization.
The invasion was preceded by a long meeting between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the start of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympics.
At the end of this meeting, the two men released a 5,000-word document, carefully written, announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is stronger than any treaty and certainly required meticulous preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi seemed to have given Poutine a free hand to invade and go to war against Ukraine.
He must be very confident and regard his confirmation as a lifetime leader of China later in the year as a mere formality.
After concentrating all powers in his hands, Xi carefully prepared the scenario in which he would be elevated to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After securing Xi's support, Poutine set about realizing his life's dream with incredible brutality.
As he approaches his 70th birthday, Poutine believes that if he wants to leave his mark on Russian history, it's now or never.
But his understanding of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
It seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar they can follow blindly.
It is precisely the opposite of a democratic society—and it is a vision that distorts the "soul" of Russia, emotional to the point of sensitivity.
As a child, I met many Russian soldiers when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I learned that they were willing to share their last piece of bread with you if you asked them.
Later, at the beginning of the 1980s, I became involved in what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I created a foundation in my native Hungary, then I actively participated in the disintegration of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, the disintegration had already begun.
I created a foundation in Russia, then did the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I created a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984, where I was the first foreigner authorized to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989, just before the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I don't know Putin personally, but I have observed his rise very closely, being fully aware of his cruelty.
He has reduced the capital of Chechnya, Grozny, to nothing. And he threatens to do the same to the capital of Ukraine, Kyiv.
Putin was once a clever operator of the KGB, but he seems to have changed recently.
Having developed a fixed idea, he seems to have lost touch with reality.
He certainly misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He expected the Russian-speaking Ukrainians to welcome Russian soldiers open-armed, but they turned out to be entirely on the same positions as the Ukrainian-speaking population.
The Ukrainians have put up an incredibly courageous resistance against an opponent that seems nothing can stop.
In July 2021, Putin published a long essay arguing that Russians and Ukrainians are really one people and that Ukrainians have been tricked by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not without historical justification, given that Kyiv was the original seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
But in the second part, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have been more cautious.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the Euromaidan protests in 2014.
The events of 2014 plunged him into a black rage.
But the Russian army performed poorly when it was ordered to attack its Ukrainian brothers.
The deep-rooted corruption in the awarding of defense contracts also played an important role in his insufficient results.
Yet, rather than feeling guilty, Putin seems to have literally gone mad.
He decided to punish Ukraine for having opposed him and seems to be acting without encountering any resistance.
He launches the entire Russian army into battle and ignores all the rules of war, including bombing the civilian population without discrimination.
Many hospitals have been hit, and the electrical network supplying the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) has been damaged.
In the besieged Marioupol, 400,000 people were without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia could very well lose the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine, and efforts are underway to purchase Russian-made MiG fighters, which Ukrainian pilots know how to fly.
That could make all the difference.
Whatever the outcome, Putin has already done wonders by strengthening the determination and unity of the EU.
Meanwhile, Xi seems to have realized that Putin is acting on his own.
On March 8, a day after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that Sino-Russian friendship remain "solid," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to express his support for their efforts to restore peace.
He wished to express maximum restraint in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
It is far from certain that Putin will heed Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed before they destroy our civilization.
